hints_latex:
The linear approximation to a function f(x) centered at the point x = a
is given by

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle L(x) = f(a) + f'(a)(x - a).
\end{align*}

sols_latex:
Using the formula for linear approximation to a function $f(x)$ near
$x = a = 8$, we have

\begin{align*}
L(x) &= f(a) + f'(a)(x - a) \\
&= \sqrt[3]{8} + \frac{1}{3(8)^{2/3}}(x - 8)\\
&= 2 + \frac{1}{12}(x - 8)
\end{align*} Since 7 is somewhat close to 8, we can estimate
$\sqrt[3]{7}$ by evaluating L(7). Thus,

\begin{align*}
L(7) = 2 - \frac{1}{12} = \frac{23}{12} \quad \Rightarrow \quad {\color{blue}\sqrt[3]{7} \approx\frac{23}{12}.}
\end{align*}
